data.chText: 摇摇晃晃地走；蹒跚；踉跄
data.enText: to walk with weak unsteady steps, as if you are about to fall

data.chText: 受伤的女人摇摇晃晃地站起身来。
data.enText: The injured woman staggered to her feet.

data.chText: 他喝醉酒，踉跄着回了家。
我们仿佛在接连不断的危机中举步维艰。
data.enText: We seem to stagger from one crisis to the next.

data.chText: 公司在1 000万英镑债务的重压下步履艰难。
data.enText: The company is staggering under the weight of a £10m debt.

data.chText: 我好不容易跌跌撞撞走了这最后几步。
data.enText: I managed to stagger the last few steps.
to shock or surprise sb very much

data.chText: 政府对此竟然不采取任何措施，我觉得不可思议。
data.enText: It staggers me that the government is doing nothing about it.
to arrange for events that would normally happen at the same time to start or happen at different times

data.chText: 参加赛跑的选手很多，他们不得不把起跑的时间错开。
data.enText: There were so many runners that they had to stagger the start.

word_means: 一种不稳定形式，部署或者秩序

means: 一种不稳定形式，部署或者秩序

ex.chText: 我们骑马还是步行?
ex.enText: Shall we ride or walk?

ex.chText: 她一直走到这条小路的尽头。
ex.enText: She walked as far as the end of the path.

ex.chText: 那个男孩告诉我应该往东走。
ex.enText: The boy told me that I should walk eastward.

synonyms.bx: 指行走的最普通用词，通常后接副词或介词。

ex.chText: 我发现他在办公室里踱来踱去。
ex.enText: I found him pacing in his office.

ex.chText: 经理在屋子里来回踱步，试图找出解决问题的办法。
ex.enText: The manager paced the floor as he tried to find a solution to the problem.

ex.chText: 老虎在笼子里走来走去。
ex.enText: The tiger paced in its cage.

synonyms.bx: 尤指因紧张、担忧、不耐烦等而来回踱步。

ex.chText: 可怜的老妇人吃力地走着，几乎都抬不动脚了。
ex.enText: The poor old woman plodded along, hardly able to lift each foot.

ex.chText: 约翰继续艰难跋涉。
ex.enText: John kept plodding on.

ex.chText: 我们不得不迈着疲倦的步子继续登山。
ex.enText: We had to plod wearily on up the hill.

synonyms.bx: 指脚步缓慢、步履艰难地行走。

ex.chText: 他蹒跚地向大门走去，伤口流着血。
ex.enText: He staggered to the gate, bleeding from his wounds.

ex.chText: 那个醉鬼摇摇晃晃地往家走去。
ex.enText: The drunken man staggered home.

ex.chText: 他摇摇晃晃地站起来。
ex.enText: He staggered to his feet.

synonyms.bx: 通常指因虚弱、负重、醉酒等而导致身体失去平衡或行走失态，强调不稳定性和失控性。

ex.chText: 她转身迈着大步走了。
ex.enText: She turned and strode off.

ex.chText: 他大踏步地向他的车走去。
ex.enText: He strode towards his car.

ex.chText: 他拔腿往回走，步子又大又快。
ex.enText: He started back, striding swiftly.

synonyms.bx: 强调步子大而有力，往往伴有或显露出匆忙、自傲、精力充沛等状态。

ex.chText: 她的宝宝刚会走道儿。
ex.enText: Her baby has just learned to toddle.

ex.chText: 我两岁的儿子摇摇摆摆地走进卧室。
ex.enText: My two-year-old son toddled into the bedroom.

synonyms.bx: 特指幼儿因学步而摇摇晃晃地小步行走。

ex.chText: 那位老人摇摇晃晃地好不容易回到了座位上。
ex.enText: The old man managed to totter back to his seat.

ex.chText: 幼儿和老人走路蹒跚。
ex.enText: Babies and aged men totter as they walk.

ex.chText: 他拄着双拐蹒跚而行，来到国王的面前。
ex.enText: With the help of two crutches, he tottered into the King's presence.

synonyms.bx: 指尤因醉酒或患病而摇摇晃晃、跌跌撞撞地行走，好像要跌倒似的。

tr: to arrange in a systematic order
example: stagger the chairs in the lecture hall

tr: astound or overwhelm, as with shock
example: She was staggered with bills after she tried to rebuild her house following the earthquake

tr: walk as if unable to control one's movements
example: The drunken man staggered into the room
He staggered along in the heavy snow

value.def: If you stagger, you walk very unsteadily, for example because you are ill or drunk.

example.ex: He lost his balance, staggered back against the rail and toppled over...
example.tran: 他失去平衡，往后趔趄了一下，撞到栏杆摔倒了。

example.ex: He was staggering and had to lean on the bar.
example.tran: 他走路摇摇晃晃，不得不靠在吧台上。

value.def: If you say that someone or something staggers on, you mean that it is only just succeeds in continuing.

example.ex: Truman allowed him to stagger on for nearly another two years.
example.tran: 杜鲁门允许他又硬撑了近两年。

example.ex: ...a government that staggered from crisis to crisis.
example.tran: 在一次又一次危机中勉强维持的政府

value.def: If something staggers you, it surprises you very much.

example.ex: I was simply staggered by the heat of the Argentinian high-summer.
example.tran: 阿根廷盛夏的酷热真让我大吃一惊。

value.def: To stagger things such as people's holidays or hours of work means to arrange them so that they do not all happen at the same time.

example.ex: During the past few years the government has staggered the summer vacation periods for students.
example.tran: 在过去几年里，政府将学生放暑假的时间相互错开。

value.tran: 使(假期或工作时间)错开
